## Summary

`packages/app-core/src/hooks/useActivityEvents.ts` subscribes to three WebSocket event streams (`pty-session-event`, `proactive-message`, `agent_event`) and calls `setEvents([...bufferRef.current])` on **every** event. When multiple events arrive in the same tick — common during code-task spawns, multi-step actions, or chatty proactive flows — React fires N re-renders, which the user sees as the Activity panel flickering.

## Reproduction

1. Open the dashboard, watch the right-side Activity panel.
2. Trigger any flow that emits multiple `agent_event`s rapidly (start a code task with sub-steps, or run anything that emits proactive nudges in quick succession).
3. Activity panel visibly flickers / re-renders rapidly.

Frequency scales with WS event volume — light usage might never trigger it; heavy use makes it constant.

## Root cause

```ts
const pushEvent = useCallback((entry) => {
  const event = { ...entry, id: makeEventId() };
  const buf = bufferRef.current;
  buf.unshift(event);
  if (buf.length > RING_BUFFER_CAP) buf.length = RING_BUFFER_CAP;
  setEvents([...buf]);  // ← new array reference every event
}, []);
```

Each `setEvents([...buf])` allocates a new top-level array reference, so React's bailout doesn't kick in. With 3 active WS subscriptions firing in bursts, you get unboundedly many renders per second. No batching, no rAF coalescing, no debounce.

## Fix (verified locally)

Coalesce bursts into one render via `requestAnimationFrame`:

```ts
const flushHandleRef = useRef<number | null>(null);

const pushEvent = useCallback((entry) => {
  const event = { ...entry, id: makeEventId() };
  const buf = bufferRef.current;
  buf.unshift(event);
  if (buf.length > RING_BUFFER_CAP) buf.length = RING_BUFFER_CAP;
  if (flushHandleRef.current !== null) return;       // already scheduled
  flushHandleRef.current = requestAnimationFrame(() => {
    flushHandleRef.current = null;
    setEvents([...bufferRef.current]);
  });
}, []);

// cancel pending flush on unmount
useEffect(() => () => {
  if (flushHandleRef.current !== null) {
    cancelAnimationFrame(flushHandleRef.current);
  }
}, []);

// clearEvents also cancels pending flush
const clearEvents = useCallback(() => {
  bufferRef.current = [];
  if (flushHandleRef.current !== null) {
    cancelAnimationFrame(flushHandleRef.current);
    flushHandleRef.current = null;
  }
  setEvents([]);
}, []);
```

After patch: at most one render per animation frame regardless of how many events fire. Visible flicker eliminated. Tested locally during a multi-step agent run.

## Why rAF and not debounce

- `requestAnimationFrame` is the right cadence for visible UI updates — anything finer is wasted work, anything coarser feels laggy.
- Survives backgrounded tabs (rAF pauses them, which is the correct behavior).
- No timeout magic numbers to tune.

## Why this matters

Subtle but persistent flicker is a "the app feels broken" UX signal even when functionally everything works. With the upcoming hyperscape / agent-orchestrator flows producing more event volume, this gets worse, not better.

## Environment

- bun 1.3.13
- React 19
- milady on `alice` (PR #105 sync)
